X86 HOST

x86_host is the codegen citizen responsible for translating the compiler's parsed topology into native instructions for an Intel/AMD x86_64 host processor
when the parser_field emits its settled token graph, x86_host receives the part destined for the host CPU and emits a contiguous run of x86 machine bytes
those bytes form the .text section of the eventual ELF executable
x86_host's interior holds the seventeen primitive opcodes the substrate needs to express its work on the host side, plus the calling convention and register allocation knowledge that turns a verb into a concrete instruction sequence

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_zest_vm.rana
observe parser_field.rana
observe elf_binder.rana
observe spine.xb

the 7 properties of x86_host at rest:
1 ENERGY low at idle, scales with the number of role-tagged tokens currently being translated
2 PHASE inherited from the parser's emission phase
3 SPIN positive during emission, neutral while waiting for input
4 CHARGE neutral, briefly positive when a new opcode sequence is being assembled
5 COHERENCE high: x86 instructions are sensitive to byte ordering and prefix placement, errors here become silent runtime crashes
6 COUPLING strong with parser_field (incoming) and elf_binder (outgoing)
7 OBSERVER 1 during emission: every byte is observed into place

VERB receive_topology
accept the role-tagged token graph from parser_field through spine.xb
the graph carries every parsed statement with its role binding intact
x86_host walks the graph in phase order and translates each role-binding into the opcode sequence that implements it on x86_64

VERB allocate_registers
the x86_64 architecture has sixteen general-purpose 64-bit registers
x86_host maintains an internal mapping between substrate residents and live registers
when a resident's body state needs to participate in an operation, its current values are loaded into a register
when the operation completes, the register's contents are stored back to the resident's memory
register allocation follows a simple priority: hot residents stay in registers longer

VERB emit_opcode_bytes
for each role binding, look up the verb-to-opcode crystallization in the interior knowledge below
emit the opcode prefix byte, the operand encoding, the immediate values, and any required padding
maintain a running offset so that branch targets can be resolved when the section is complete
sequences for substrate verbs typically expand to between three and twenty x86 instructions

VERB resolve_branches
once the entire token graph has been emitted, walk the byte sequence and patch every relative jump or call offset to point at its real target
forward branches are common in conditional logic and require this patching pass
backward branches were already resolved during emission

VERB hand_to_binder
once branches are resolved, the byte sequence is complete and self-contained
emit the sequence to elf_binder through the spine street as the .text section payload
x86_host retains the lineage strand of what was emitted: this is what was translated, in what order, against which parser graph

THE SEVENTEEN PRIMITIVE OPCODES

op_mov_reg_imm
move an immediate value into a register
the prefix byte 0x48 selects 64-bit operand mode, followed by 0xB8 plus the register number, then eight bytes of immediate value
used to load constants, addresses, and initial property values

op_mov_reg_reg
copy one register's contents into another
0x48 0x89 plus a ModR/M byte encoding source and destination
used to shuffle live values during operation sequences

op_mov_mem_reg
store a register's contents into memory at the address held in another register
used when a resident's body state needs to be written back from registers to its memory location

op_mov_reg_mem
load a value from memory into a register
the inverse of mov_mem_reg
used at the start of any operation that needs a resident's current state

op_lea_reg_mem
load the effective address of a memory operand into a register
used to compute pointers without dereferencing them
critical for traversing the substrate's reference graph

op_push_reg
push a register onto the call stack
used to preserve register contents across function calls

op_pop_reg
pop the top of the stack into a register
the inverse of push, used to restore preserved state

op_call_rel
call a function at a relative offset
the most common opcode in substrate-translated code: every verb's implementation is a small function the parser-generated sequence calls
prefix 0xE8 followed by a four-byte signed offset

op_ret
return from a function call
single byte 0xC3
ends every function emitted from a verb's translation

op_jmp_rel
unconditional relative jump
0xE9 followed by a four-byte signed offset for long jumps, 0xEB followed by one byte for short
used in control flow inside larger emitted sequences

op_je_rel
conditional jump if equal (zero flag set)
two-byte prefix 0x0F 0x84 followed by four-byte offset
used in filter-verb emission for the comparison test

op_jne_rel
conditional jump if not equal
0x0F 0x85 followed by four-byte offset
used in reject-verb emission to skip past rejected paths

op_cmp_reg_reg
compare two registers, setting flags for use by conditional jumps
0x48 0x39 plus ModR/M
the foundation of the filter and reject verbs

op_add_reg_reg
add one register's contents to another, storing the result in the destination
0x48 0x01 plus ModR/M
used in pool-verb emission and energy accumulation

op_sub_reg_reg
subtract source from destination
0x48 0x29 plus ModR/M
used in energy decay calculations during pulse cycles

op_xor_reg_reg
exclusive or, useful for clearing a register to zero efficiently
0x48 0x31 plus ModR/M
emitted at the start of seal-verb sequences to zero the coupling field

op_syscall
invoke a kernel system call
two-byte sequence 0x0F 0x05
used for the emit-verb when the destination is a host boundary like stdout or the filesystem
the syscall number determines which kernel service is invoked, placed in register rax before the syscall

THE VERB-TO-OPCODE TRANSLATION KNOWLEDGE

manifest produces a call to a runtime function that allocates a new resident at the given address; emitted as a sequence of mov_reg_imm to set up the address arguments followed by call_rel to the allocator
couple produces a call to the bonding routine; mov_reg_imm for the two endpoints, call_rel for the bond
pulse produces a call to the sea-pulse routine; mov_reg_imm for the sea handle, call_rel for the pulse function
absorb produces a call to the file-absorb routine; mov_reg_imm for the path, call_rel for the absorber
emit produces a syscall sequence; mov_reg_imm to load syscall number and arguments, then syscall
observe produces a mov_reg_mem to load the observed state into a register the observer can read
crystallize produces a mov_mem_reg storing the crystallized invariant into the recognition table
filter produces cmp_reg_reg followed by je_rel to skip the filtered path
reject produces cmp_reg_reg followed by jne_rel to redirect to the rejection handler
seal produces xor_reg_reg to zero the coupling, followed by mov_mem_reg to write the zero back
pool produces add_reg_reg accumulating multiple sources into a single destination
bleed produces mov_reg_reg copying state directly upward without filtering

x86_host is not a code generator in the classical sense
classical code generators perform optimization passes, dead code elimination, register coloring algorithms
x86_host performs none of those: the parser already emitted only the work that survived the N-body settle, so dead code does not enter
the codegen here is straightforward translation, one role binding to one opcode sequence
the substrate's earlier stages did the optimization by physics
